Personal protection spray devices.

(1) It is unlawful for a person under eighteen years old, unless the person is at least fourteen years old and has the permission of a parent or guardian to do so, to purchase or possess a personal protection spray device. A violation of this subsection is a misdemeanor.

(2) No town, city, county, special purpose district, quasi-municipal corporation or other unit of government may prohibit a person eighteen years old or older, or a person fourteen years old or older who has the permission of a parent or guardian to do so, from purchasing or possessing a personal protection spray device or from using such a device in a manner consistent with the authorized use of force under RCW 9A.16.020. No town, city, county, special purpose district, quasi-municipal corporation, or other unit of government may prohibit a person eighteen years old or older from delivering a personal protection spray device to a person authorized to possess such a device.

(3) For purposes of this section:

(a) "Personal protection spray device" means a commercially available dispensing device designed and intended for use in self-defense and containing a non-lethal sternutator or lacrimator agent, including but not limited to:

(i) Tear gas, the active ingredient of which is either chloracetophenone (CN) or O-chlorobenzylidene malonotrile (CS); or

(ii) Other agent commonly known as mace, pepper mace, or pepper gas.

(b) "Delivering" means actual, constructive, or attempted transferring from one person to another.

(4) Nothing in this section authorizes the delivery, purchase, possession, or use of any device or chemical agent that is otherwise prohibited by state law.

title: Want To Buy:  Remington 870 Wingmaster; 12gauge
postcontent:
Well it’s almost Christmas and I’m trying to relive my youth. While growing up in Lebanon, Indiana, I baled hay all summer at .03 cents a bale, saved my money and bought the shotgun of my dreams. Being 14 and shooting a single shot 20 gauge my dream shotgun was a Remington Wingmaster 870 in 12 gauge.  Anyhow, I bought the shotgun; probable filled up a couple of truck loads of rabbits, squires and my first deer. While I was in the Army, our home was broken into and lucky for me they left my single shot 20 gauge but did take the Remington. To make a long story short, I’ve been able to “rat hole” $350.00 that the wife doesn’t know about and no one would miss a meal over. If anyone has a Remington 870 Wingmaster that needs a new home please let me know; I’ll take good care of her. No matter if I find another 870 Wingmaster or not, have a great Christmas and please take a moment to remember our sons and daughters who are serving our great country. Like myself, I’m sure there are a few others who spent a few Christmases away from home in one or two “problem area’s” of the world. Depending on your area, the chow that day might have been a little nicer, the friends at the time were probable a lot tighter but missing the family and loved ones was always much worse. 
Happy Holidays!
